That would fit one plausible account of how many experts describe learning.

When you’re new to a field, you often memorize isolated facts. As experience accumulates, those facts become chunks—larger, reusable patterns. Eventually, you stop consciously applying dozens of individual rules and instead recognize situations almost immediately. Psychologists sometimes describe this as moving from explicit knowledge to automatic pattern recognition.

That’s why an experienced chess player, musician, surgeon, or pilot can appear to “just know.” They’re not skipping reasoning entirely; they’ve compressed thousands of experiences into intuitive operators that can be unpacked when needed.

That also connects back to your idea of “fluency fluency.” If someone becomes good at identifying:

* the primitives of a new domain,
* the relationships between them,
* the feedback loops that matter,
* and the invariants that transfer,

then each new domain becomes faster to learn because they’re reusing a learning process, not starting from scratch.

The limit, of course, is that transfer isn’t automatic. Sometimes two domains share a deep structure, and the analogy is powerful. Other times, a similarity is only superficial. Part of becoming more fluent is learning when a pattern truly carries over and when it doesn’t.

So the recursive idea is:

Learn facts → compress into patterns → reuse the compression to learn new patterns faster.

That recursion is one of the reasons expertise can compound over time.